  ('color-call-cone-cut', 'Color-Call Cone Cut improves the athlete’s ability to coordinate the foot, ankle, knee, hip, trunk, and visual system during external cue selects the cut direction. Field-sport agility depends on producing force quickly, absorbing force safely, and reorienting the body without extra steps; this drill isolates one piece of that chain and then links it to a usable athletic action.', 'Belongs in output / reactive_agility_tumbling_output because the drill’s main adaptation is reactive perception-action agility. The placement respects the Vortex rule that high-intent speed, COD, and reactive work must stay fresh, while control and tissue-capacity work sit in resilience or capacity rather than being disguised as warm-up conditioning.', 'Place in the Output block after warm-up, movement prep, and basic braking rehearsal. Use low volume, high intent, and full rest before strength or conditioning.', 'Most common error is adding too many reps, too little rest, or too much speed before the athlete can brake and align. Do not turn this into a fatigue circuit when the goal is speed, perception, or clean COD mechanics.', 'Scale first by speed, amplitude, decision complexity, and cut angle. Add velocity, sharper angles, defenders, balls, sticks, or resistance only after the athlete can show quiet stops and clean exits on both sides.'),
  ('ball-drop-reaction-sprint', 'Ball Drop Reaction Sprint improves the athlete’s ability to coordinate the foot, ankle, knee, hip, trunk, and visual system during visual reaction into acceleration. Field-sport agility depends on producing force quickly, absorbing force safely, and reorienting the body without extra steps; this drill isolates one piece of that chain and then links it to a usable athletic action.', 'Belongs in output / reactive_agility_tumbling_output because the drill’s main adaptation is reactive perception-action agility. The placement respects the Vortex rule that high-intent speed, COD, and reactive work must stay fresh, while control and tissue-capacity work sit in resilience or capacity rather than being disguised as warm-up conditioning.', 'Place in the Output block after warm-up, movement prep, and basic braking rehearsal. Use low volume, high intent, and full rest before strength or conditioning.', 'Most common error is adding too many reps, too little rest, or too much speed before the athlete can brake and align. Do not turn this into a fatigue circuit when the goal is speed, perception, or clean COD mechanics.', 'Scale first by speed, amplitude, decision complexity, and cut angle. Add velocity, sharper angles, defenders, balls, sticks, or resistance only after the athlete can show quiet stops and clean exits on both sides.'),
  ('tennis-ball-lateral-reaction', 'Tennis Ball Lateral Reaction improves the athlete’s ability to coordinate the foot, ankle, knee, hip, trunk, and visual system during reactive first step and lateral catch. Field-sport agility depends on producing force quickly, absorbing force safely, and reorienting the body without extra steps; this drill isolates one piece of that chain and then links it to a usable athletic action.', 'Belongs in movement_intelligence / perception_action_reactive_movement because the drill’s main adaptation is reactive perception-action agility. The placement respects the Vortex rule that high-intent speed, COD, and reactive work must stay fresh, while control and tissue-capacity work sit in resilience or capacity rather than being disguised as warm-up conditioning.', 'Place after warm-up and before true Output. Keep reps crisp; the goal is coordination, perception, and clean timing, not fatigue.', 'Most common error is adding too many reps, too little rest, or too much speed before the athlete can brake and align. Do not turn this into a fatigue circuit when the goal is speed, perception, or clean COD mechanics.', 'Scale first by speed, amplitude, decision complexity, and cut angle. Add velocity, sharper angles, defenders, balls, sticks, or resistance only after the athlete can show quiet stops and clean exits on both sides.'),
  ('partner-chase-to-reactive-45-cut', 'Partner Chase to Reactive 45 Cut improves the athlete’s ability to coordinate the foot, ankle, knee, hip, trunk, and visual system during pursuer pressure creates perception-action demand. Field-sport agility depends on producing force quickly, absorbing force safely, and reorienting the body without extra steps; this drill isolates one piece of that chain and then links it to a usable athletic action.', 'Belongs in output / reactive_agility_tumbling_output because the drill’s main adaptation is reactive perception-action agility. The placement respects the Vortex rule that high-intent speed, COD, and reactive work must stay fresh, while control and tissue-capacity work sit in resilience or capacity rather than being disguised as warm-up conditioning.', 'Place in the Output block after warm-up, movement prep, and basic braking rehearsal. Use low volume, high intent, and full rest before strength or conditioning.', 'Most common error is adding too many reps, too little rest, or too much speed before the athlete can brake and align. Do not turn this into a fatigue circuit when the goal is speed, perception, or clean COD mechanics.', 'Scale first by speed, amplitude, decision complexity, and cut angle. Add velocity, sharper angles, defenders, balls, sticks, or resistance only after the athlete can show quiet stops and clean exits on both sides.'),
  ('4-cone-reactive-drill', '4-Cone Reactive Drill improves the athlete’s ability to coordinate the foot, ankle, knee, hip, trunk, and visual system during coach call or point changes exit cone. Field-sport agility depends on producing force quickly, absorbing force safely, and reorienting the body without extra steps; this drill isolates one piece of that chain and then links it to a usable athletic action.', 'Belongs in output / reactive_agility_tumbling_output because the drill’s main adaptation is reactive perception-action agility. The placement respects the Vortex rule that high-intent speed, COD, and reactive work must stay fresh, while control and tissue-capacity work sit in resilience or capacity rather than being disguised as warm-up conditioning.', 'Place in the Output block after warm-up, movement prep, and basic braking rehearsal. Use low volume, high intent, and full rest before strength or conditioning.', 'Most common error is adding too many reps, too little rest, or too much speed before the athlete can brake and align. Do not turn this into a fatigue circuit when the goal is speed, perception, or clean COD mechanics.', 'Scale first by speed, amplitude, decision complexity, and cut angle. Add velocity, sharper angles, defenders, balls, sticks, or resistance only after the athlete can show quiet stops and clean exits on both sides.'),
  ('rear-foot-elevated-split-squat-iso-cut-position', 'Rear-Foot Elevated Split Squat Iso Cut Position improves the athlete’s ability to coordinate the foot, ankle, knee, hip, trunk, and visual system during isometric single-leg force in cut-like angles. Field-sport agility depends on producing force quickly, absorbing force safely, and reorienting the body without extra steps; this drill isolates one piece of that chain and then links it to a usable athletic action.', 'Belongs in capacity / squat_knee_dominant_strength because the drill’s main adaptation is strength support for cutting brakes. The placement respects the Vortex rule that high-intent speed, COD, and reactive work must stay fresh, while control and tissue-capacity work sit in resilience or capacity rather than being disguised as warm-up conditioning.', 'Place after Output as strength support for athletes who need better plant, push, and braking positions.', 'Most common error is adding too many reps, too little rest, or too much speed before the athlete can brake and align. Do not turn this into a fatigue circuit when the goal is speed, perception, or clean COD mechanics.', 'Scale first by speed, amplitude, decision complexity, and cut angle. Add velocity, sharper angles, defenders, balls, sticks, or resistance only after the athlete can show quiet stops and clean exits on both sides.'),
  ('short-lever-copenhagen-plank', 'Short-Lever Copenhagen Plank improves the athlete’s ability to coordinate the foot, ankle, knee, hip, trunk, and visual system during adductor capacity for lateral cuts and groin resilience. Field-sport agility depends on producing force quickly, absorbing force safely, and reorienting the body without extra steps; this drill isolates one piece of that chain and then links it to a usable athletic action.', 'Belongs in resilience / trunk_pelvis_anti_movement_control because the drill’s main adaptation is adductor and trunk resilience. The placement respects the Vortex rule that high-intent speed, COD, and reactive work must stay fresh, while control and tissue-capacity work sit in resilience or capacity rather than being disguised as warm-up conditioning.', 'Place after technical warm-up or after the primary Output/Capacity work as a braking, landing, or tissue-control block.', 'Most common error is adding too many reps, too little rest, or too much speed before the athlete can brake and align. Do not turn this into a fatigue circuit when the goal is speed, perception, or clean COD mechanics.', 'Scale first by speed, amplitude, decision complexity, and cut angle. Add velocity, sharper angles, defenders, balls, sticks, or resistance only after the athlete can show quiet stops and clean exits on both sides.'),
  ('repeat-cod-shuttle-intervals', 'Repeat COD Shuttle Intervals improves the athlete’s ability to coordinate the foot, ankle, knee, hip, trunk, and visual system during maintain posture and braking quality under fatigue. Field-sport agility depends on producing force quickly, absorbing force safely, and reorienting the body without extra steps; this drill isolates one piece of that chain and then links it to a usable athletic action.', 'Belongs in sustained_capacity / conditioning_intervals because the drill’s main adaptation is repeatability under fatigue. The placement respects the Vortex rule that high-intent speed, COD, and reactive work must stay fresh, while control and tissue-capacity work sit in resilience or capacity rather than being disguised as warm-up conditioning.', 'Place late in the session after Output and Capacity work when the goal is repeatability under fatigue while preserving mechanics.', 'Most common error is adding too many reps, too little rest, or too much speed before the athlete can brake and align. Do not turn this into a fatigue circuit when the goal is speed, perception, or clean COD mechanics.', 'Scale first by speed, amplitude, decision complexity, and cut angle. Add velocity, sharper angles, defenders, balls, sticks, or resistance only after the athlete can show quiet stops and clean exits on both sides.')
